---
import CalculatorLayout from "../../layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro";
import { DataEgressCostCalculator } from "../../components/calculators/DataEgressCost";

const title = "AWS Cross-Region Data Transfer Cost Calculator";
const description =
  "Convert known AWS region-pair transfer volume into spend from source, destination, direction, monthly GB, and an effective cross-region rate.";
---
<CalculatorLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/calculators/cross-region-transfer-cost-calculator"
  intro="This calculator is the region-pair transfer bill-conversion page: use it after source region, destination region, traffic direction, monthly GB, and effective cross-region rate are already known. It does not own the replication workflow, replica storage model, request overhead model, or S3-specific replication bill boundary."
  examples={[
    "If you replicate 3,000 GB/month across regions at $0.02/GB, estimated transfer cost is $60/month.",
  ]}
  includes={[
    "Cross-region transfer estimate from GB/month and $/GB pricing.",
    "Useful for replication, DR, and multi-region architectures.",
  ]}
  excludes={[
    "Provider-specific free tiers, discounts, and tiered steps.",
    "Replica storage costs (model separately).",
  ]}
  how={[
    "Monthly cost = cross-region GB x price per GB.",
    "Enter your provider's cross-region transfer price for the source/destination regions.",
    "This page ignores free intra-zone traffic and tiering unless you reflect it in the inputs."
  ]}
  faqs={[
    {
      q: "Is cross-region transfer the same as internet egress?",
      a: "No. Providers often price cross-region differently than public internet egress."
    },
    {
      q: "Does replication count both directions?",
      a: "Typically replication traffic is billed on the outbound side. Confirm the billing direction for your service."
    }
  ]}
  lastUpdated="2026-07-22"
  related={[
    { href: "/calculators/storage-replication-cost-calculator", label: "Storage replication" },
    { href: "/calculators/object-storage-cost-calculator", label: "Object storage cost" },
    { href: "/calculators/data-egress-cost-calculator", label: "Internet egress cost" },
    { href: "/guides/aws-vpc-data-transfer/", label: "Guide: VPC data transfer" },
    { href: "/guides/aws-cross-az-data-transfer-cost", label: "Guide: cross-AZ transfer cost" },
  ]}
>
  <DataEgressCostCalculator
    transferLabel="Cross-region transfer (GB / month)"
    priceLabel="Cross-region price ($ / GB)"
    defaultGbPerMonth={3000}
    defaultPricePerGbUsd={0.02}
  client:load />
  <div class="prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Cross-region transfer is usually directional, not symmetric</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">
      This page is for one of the easiest cloud charges to misread: traffic that moves between regions. The billing
      event is often <strong>directional</strong>, so a clean estimate starts with region pair and traffic direction,
      not just total bytes moved.
    </p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">
      The calculator converts a known transfer line into spend. Use the replication workflow, replication-volume
      measurement, or storage calculator when the copied GB, replica storage, request overhead, or copy rule still needs
      to be worked out.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Steady-state replication</strong>: predictable monthly copy volume from the primary path.</li>
      <li><strong>Backfill or migration</strong>: one-time bulk transfer that should never be mixed into the normal month.</li>
      <li><strong>DR or failover</strong>: rare but expensive spikes that need their own peak scenario.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What people usually miss on cross-region bills</h2>
    <p>
      The transfer line itself is only one part of a multi-region decision. Teams often estimate the copied GB but miss
      the fact that replica storage, destination reads, and backlog catch-up events all have different billing behavior.
      That is why this page should stay focused on the transfer line and hand off the adjacent lines to other tools.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Directionality</strong>: confirm whether the cost is charged on the outbound side only.</li>
      <li><strong>Event separation</strong>: migrations and backlog replays belong in a separate peak case.</li>
      <li><strong>Neighboring charges</strong>: replica storage and destination-side processing should not be hidden in this number.</li>
      <li><strong>Compression changes</strong>: payload optimization may reduce copied GB without changing request count.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What to capture before you trust the estimate</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Identify the specific source and destination region pair instead of using a generic cross-region assumption.</li>
      <li>Split steady replication from migrations, backfills, DR drills, and failover recovery windows.</li>
      <li>Keep cross-region traffic separate from internet egress and cross-AZ transfer even if the same system generates all three.</li>
      <li>Review whether the real business question is transfer-only or a wider multi-region cost model.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Steady-state vs event-driven region transfer</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Scenario</th>
          <th>GB/month</th>
          <th>Direction</th>
          <th>Drivers</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Baseline</td>
          <td>Expected</td>
          <td>Primary -> DR</td>
          <td>Steady replication</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Peak</td>
          <td>High</td>
          <td>Primary -> DR</td>
          <td>Backfill/migration</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>How to review the first real cross-region bill</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Check whether the billed direction matches the direction you modeled for the region pair.</li>
      <li>Keep one-time migrations and failover windows outside the recurring baseline after the event is complete.</li>
      <li>Investigate destination storage, replay traffic, or read behavior before blaming the transfer rate itself.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Next steps</h2>
    <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:0">
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/">Guides</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/">All calculators</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/storage-replication-cost-calculator/">Storage replication</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/object-storage-cost-calculator/">Object storage cost</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/data-egress-cost-calculator/">Internet egress cost</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/aws-vpc-data-transfer/">Guide: VPC data transfer</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</CalculatorLayout>
